62    /**
63    * This is the main class for using Gson. Gson is typically used by first constructing a
64    * Gson instance and then invoking {@link #toJson(Object)} or {@link #fromJson(String, Class)}
65    * methods on it. Gson instances are Thread-safe so you can reuse them freely across multiple
66    * threads.
67    *
68    * <p>You can create a Gson instance by invoking {@code new Gson()} if the default configuration
69    * is all you need. You can also use {@link GsonBuilder} to build a Gson instance with various
70    * configuration options such as versioning support, pretty printing, custom
71    * {@link JsonSerializer}s, {@link JsonDeserializer}s, and {@link InstanceCreator}s.</p>
72    *
73    * <p>Here is an example of how Gson is used for a simple Class:
74    *
75    * <pre>
76    * Gson gson = new Gson(); // Or use new GsonBuilder().create();
77    * MyType target = new MyType();
78    * String json = gson.toJson(target); // serializes target to Json
79    * MyType target2 = gson.fromJson(json, MyType.class); // deserializes json into target2
80    * </pre>
81    *
82    * <p>If the object that your are serializing/deserializing is a {@code ParameterizedType}
83    * (i.e. contains at least one type parameter and may be an array) then you must use the
84    * {@link #toJson(Object, Type)} or {@link #fromJson(String, Type)} method. Here is an
85    * example for serializing and deserializing a {@code ParameterizedType}:
86    *
87    * <pre>
88    * Type listType = new TypeToken&lt;List&lt;String&gt;&gt;() {}.getType();
89    * List&lt;String&gt; target = new LinkedList&lt;String&gt;();
90    * target.add("blah");
91    *
92    * Gson gson = new Gson();
93    * String json = gson.toJson(target, listType);
94    * List&lt;String&gt; target2 = gson.fromJson(json, listType);
95    * </pre>
96    *
97    * <p>See the <a href="https://sites.google.com/site/gson/gson-user-guide">Gson User Guide</a>
98    * for a more complete set of examples.</p>
99    *
100    * @see com.google.gson.reflect.TypeToken
101    *
102    * @author Inderjeet Singh
103    * @author Joel Leitch
104    * @author Jesse Wilson
105    */

160    /**
161    * Constructs a Gson object with default configuration. The default configuration has the
162    * following settings:
163    * <ul>
164    * <li>The JSON generated by <code>toJson</code> methods is in compact representation. This
165    * means that all the unneeded white-space is removed. You can change this behavior with
166    * {@link GsonBuilder#setPrettyPrinting()}. </li>
167    * <li>The generated JSON omits all the fields that are null. Note that nulls in arrays are
168    * kept as is since an array is an ordered list. Moreover, if a field is not null, but its
169    * generated JSON is empty, the field is kept. You can configure Gson to serialize null values
170    * by setting {@link GsonBuilder#serializeNulls()}.</li>
171    * <li>Gson provides default serialization and deserialization for Enums, {@link Map},
172    * {@link java.net.URL}, {@link java.net.URI}, {@link java.util.Locale}, {@link java.util.Date},
173    * {@link java.math.BigDecimal}, and {@link java.math.BigInteger} classes. If you would prefer
174    * to change the default representation, you can do so by registering a type adapter through
175    * {@link GsonBuilder#registerTypeAdapter(Type, Object)}. </li>
176    * <li>The default Date format is same as {@link java.text.DateFormat#DEFAULT}. This format
177    * ignores the millisecond portion of the date during serialization. You can change
178    * this by invoking {@link GsonBuilder#setDateFormat(int)} or
179    * {@link GsonBuilder#setDateFormat(String)}. </li>
180    * <li>By default, Gson ignores the {@link com.google.gson.annotations.Expose} annotation.
181    * You can enable Gson to serialize/deserialize only those fields marked with this annotation
182    * through {@link GsonBuilder#excludeFieldsWithoutExposeAnnotation()}. </li>
183    * <li>By default, Gson ignores the {@link com.google.gson.annotations.Since} annotation. You
184    * can enable Gson to use this annotation through {@link GsonBuilder#setVersion(double)}.</li>
185    * <li>The default field naming policy for the output Json is same as in Java. So, a Java class
186    * field <code>versionNumber</code> will be output as <code>&quot;versionNumber&quot;</code> in
187    * Json. The same rules are applied for mapping incoming Json to the Java classes. You can
188    * change this policy through {@link GsonBuilder#setFieldNamingPolicy(FieldNamingPolicy)}.</li>
189    * <li>By default, Gson excludes <code>transient</code> or <code>static</code> fields from
190    * consideration for serialization and deserialization. You can change this behavior through
191    * {@link GsonBuilder#excludeFieldsWithModifiers(int...)}.</li>
192    * </ul>
193    */

518    /**
519    * This method is used to get an alternate type adapter for the specified type. This is used
520    * to access a type adapter that is overridden by a {@link TypeAdapterFactory} that you
521    * may have registered. This features is typically used when you want to register a type
522    * adapter that does a little bit of work but then delegates further processing to the Gson
523    * default type adapter. Here is an example:
524    * <p>Let's say we want to write a type adapter that counts the number of objects being read
525    * from or written to JSON. We can achieve this by writing a type adapter factory that uses
526    * the <code>getDelegateAdapter</code> method:
527    * <pre> {@code
528    * class StatsTypeAdapterFactory implements TypeAdapterFactory {
529    * public int numReads = 0;
530    * public int numWrites = 0;
531    * public <T> TypeAdapter<T> create(Gson gson, TypeToken<T> type) {
532    * final TypeAdapter<T> delegate = gson.getDelegateAdapter(this, type);
533    * return new TypeAdapter<T>() {
534    * public void write(JsonWriter out, T value) throws IOException {
535    * ++numWrites;
536    * delegate.write(out, value);
537    * }
538    * public T read(JsonReader in) throws IOException {
539    * ++numReads;
540    * return delegate.read(in);
541    * }
542    * };
543    * }
544    * }
545    * } </pre>
546    * This factory can now be used like this:
547    * <pre> {@code
548    * StatsTypeAdapterFactory stats = new StatsTypeAdapterFactory();
549    * Gson gson = new GsonBuilder().registerTypeAdapterFactory(stats).create();
550    * // Call gson.toJson() and fromJson methods on objects
551    * System.out.println("Num JSON reads" + stats.numReads);
552    * System.out.println("Num JSON writes" + stats.numWrites);
553    * }</pre>
554    * Note that this call will skip all factories registered before {@code skipPast}. In case of
555    * multiple TypeAdapterFactories registered it is up to the caller of this function to insure
556    * that the order of registration does not prevent this method from reaching a factory they
557    * would expect to reply from this call.
558    * Note that since you can not override type adapter factories for String and Java primitive
559    * types, our stats factory will not count the number of String or primitives that will be
560    * read or written.
561    * @param skipPast The type adapter factory that needs to be skipped while searching for
562    * a matching type adapter. In most cases, you should just pass <i>this</i> (the type adapter
563    * factory from where {@code getDelegateAdapter} method is being invoked).
564    * @param type Type for which the delegate adapter is being searched for.
565    *
566    * @since 2.2
567    */
